event_description: This class seeks to improve participants' proficiency in basic aquatic skills (including rotary breathing, surface dives and treading) and the six basic swimming strokes (i.e., front crawl, back crawl, butterfly, breaststroke, elementary backstroke and sidestroke). This class builds on the basic aquatic skills and water safety skills and concepts learned in level 1. Participants begin to perform skills at a slightly more advanced level and begin gaining rudimentary propulsive skills on both the front and the back. Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

The primary purpose of the lifeguard training program is to provide entry-level lifeguard skills and knowledge to prevent, recognize, and respond to emergencies and to provide care for sudden illnesses until advanced medical personnel arrives and takes over. This program includes a lifeguard training course with aquatics-specific first aid and cardio-pulmonary resuscitation (CPR) training. Note: Participants MUST pass the pre-test on the first day of class. The test consists of the following: 300-yard swim; tread water for 2 minute without the use of arms; swim 20 yards, then surface dive to retrieve a 10-lb brick, swim back to the starting point with both hands on the brick, and climb out of the water without assistance, skill must be performed in under 1 minute 40 seconds. Depending on the skills of the participants and their comprehension of the materials presented, the participants may be dismissed early or need to stay later each day.

Participating toddlers must be accompanied by a participating adult. As with    every art class, dress for a mess! Appropriate for toddlers 2 to 4 years,    accompanied by a participating adult.

event_name: Jewelry Workshop: Woven Seed Bead Jewelry
event_description: Learn    basic peyote stitching and right-angle weaving techniques to create custom    seed bead jewelry! Students will be guided through the process of planning    and threading, explore creative variations to personalize pieces, incorporate    patterns, colors, and textures into woven designs, and properly secure thread    for durability and professional finishing. Students will take home their own    unique woven piece of wearable art! All tools and materials provided.

There is much more in Hatha yoga practice than poses. In this series, we still explore practices aimed to improve our physical well-being through asanas (poses); we also introduce practices that include pranayama (breath expansion) techniques, and finally we experience the benefits of simple meditation techniques. The intention is awareness at a physical, mental and emotional level on as well as off the mat.

event_description: Unleash    your imagination and explore the world of art through hands-on projects.  This class is for young artists who like to    experiment, create & discover new techniques, & get inspired by being    around other young artists. Students will explore color, shape, & texture while    developing their creativity, problem-solving & confidence in their    art!

Members    of the Randall Museum Clay Club tackle a variety of fun projects both    functional & sculptural, experimental and playful. Members will learn    basic clay building skills making projects like animal figures,    self-portraits, cups, boxes, bowls, and sp much more. We'll explore slab,    coil, and pinching methods as well as a range of decorative texturing and    glazing techniques.

Explore the vast, imaginative possibilities of clay in the Randall's open studio setting. Hone your skills throwing on a wheel or hand-building, making something for use or building sculptural pieces. If you have some experience in clay, whether back in high school or recently, and would like to develop a project and take your skills to the next level, this class is for you. Get one-on-one guidance and support from our experienced instructors.

event_name: Disability Sports: Power Chair Soccer (Golden State Ducks)
event_description: Power Soccer is a disability sport, played in specially modified power wheelchairs. The Golden State Ducks SF Power Soccer program is presented by SF Recreation and Parks and Bay Area Outreach and Recreation Program (BORP), this program welcomes beginner and experienced players. Participants can enjoy practice play or high-level tournament competition!  If you do not have your own power soccer chair, we may be able to provide a chair for you to use to help you get started.  And if you want to keep playing, we can help connect you with resources for purchasing your own chair!  After you register, or if you have questions or want to check out the sport before you register, reach out to goldenstateducks@gmail.com. Eureka Valley Recreation Center is located on 100 Collingwood St, San Francisco, CA 94114.

This class should improve participants' proficiency in performing the swimming strokes that were introduced in Level 3. Participants perform these strokes with increased proficiency and can swim them for greater distances. In addition, participants learn the arm actions that accompany the scissors kick and breaststroke kick to begin performing the sidestroke and breaststroke at rudimentary proficiency levels. Participants also learn the back crawl and butterfly at rudimentary proficiency levels, in addition to the basics of performing a simple open turn at a wall. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 3.

MASTER YOUR FIRE LEAD WITH CLARITY A 26 WEEK ANGER MANAGEMENT GROUP Feeling overwhelmed by anger? You’re not alone; you don’t have to face it alone. Our supportive anger management group offers a safe space to explore the roots of your anger, build healthier coping strategies, and regain control of your emotional responses. Whether your anger is affecting your relationships, work, or personal well-being, we’re here to help you channel it into positive change. Join us and take the first step toward a calmer, more empowered you. Every Thursday 4:30 pm – 6:30 pm July 17th 2025 – Jan. 8th 2026 FAIDA CALDWELL FCALDWELL@YMCASF.ORG 415 822 9404

Explore    the awesome world of 3D printing and modeling! You’ll jump right in designing    and building your own simple three-dimensional objects in TinkerCad, a 3D    modeling program. Then you’ll export your files to our MakerBot Replicator 3D    printers, and learn how to finish & refine the printed objects. Your    creative, design and digital skill sets will expand as you refine your    designs through prototypes and revisions.

The    Maunupau Method/Learning & Fun Tennis System(LAFTS) curriculum uses a    progressive learning module to teach entry level students to play tennis with    proper technique. Students can expect to learn grips, swing flight paths,    stances, the art of the rally, shoulders being perpendicular to the net,    & match play.
Pickleball is a fast-paced and challenging sport that can provide hours of fun and excitement for players of all skill levels. Come drop in to play the fastest growing sport in America.

Join us    for a fun-filled, hands-on art class designed for kids and their caregivers!    Get ready to unleash your creativity as we dive into making fun Valentine    cards and other Valentine-related objects using recycled materials. We will    provide an incredible variety of recyclable and mixed media materials,    including cardboard, paper, fabric, air-dry clay, pastels, and paint. This    class is not only a fantastic way to promote sustainability, but it also    offers an excellent opportunity for you to work with your child and ignite    their imagination! Adult participation is essential and mandatory, and spaces    are limited. If you have more than 1 child participating, you must enroll for    2 spaces.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats—an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

event_description: Learn  about different gemstones and how to close off a head pin properly to make  & take home your own sterling silver earrings. The  studio is outfitted with all the tools and equipment to make a unique pair of  earrings you can take home the same day. Clay is available for purchase at the studio with a    100-pound clay limit per session. No outside clay or glazes allowed. Students    must purchase a basic pottery tool kit prior to the first day of class.    Suggested materials list can be found at sharonartstudio.org. This is a fun, easy way to gain experience with basic design software and the precision digital maker tools in the Fab Lab. No previous experience necessary.

Discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats—an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

This level continues to focus on building more comfort and enjoyment in the water using songs, games and play. While introducing more structured play in the areas of bobbing, breath control, floating, gliding and kicking on front and back, in addition to arm rotations and other elementary skills. Children ages 3 and under are required to wear swim diapers while in the pool. The ratio is 1 adult per child. Swim classes are limited to one class per person per session.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

event_description: ** The times for this class has changed to 6:30-9:30pm**Are    you a jewelry enthusiast? Join our foundational class for those looking to    start their journey in jewelry-making. We will explore the basic and vital    techniques to jewelry fabrication and metalsmithing. Students will learn how    to properly cut, saw, anneal, texture, shape, solder, and polish metal in our    8-week introduction to jewelry fabrication. Our wonderful jewelry studio is    outfitted with all the tools and equipment to take your jewelry making to the    next level and beyond. Class fee includes the use of tools and materials for    two introductory project such as a pendant, keychain, a ring, or earrings in    brass or copper. Students who wish to use materials beyond what is provided    need to have the approval of the instructor and be responsible for purchasing    and safe storage. Additional silver and gemstones can be purchased in class    for a fee, payable to the instructor. Jewelry making requires normal hand    dexterity. New students must attend the first class to receive instruction    that will not be repeated. Tools and materials available. The Jewelry Studio    is located on the upper floor, with stair access only. For accommodations    requests or accessibility questions, please contact rpdaccess@sfgov.org or    415-831-6841. Please note that submitting your request at least two weeks    before the beginning of the class will help ensure availability.

event_name: Hatha Yoga and Ashtanga Yoga Fusion
event_description: A Yoga    style from Mind to Body and it’s a step to Hatha Yoga which says from Body to    Mind. In addition, with a yoga practice of Fusion Yoga - Ashtang (Eight    Limbs) Yoga and Hatha Yoga.

There is much more in Hatha yoga practice than poses. In this series, we still explore practices aimed to improve our physical well-being through asanas (poses); we also introduce practices that include pranayama (breath expansion) techniques, and finally we experience the benefits of simple meditation techniques. The intention is awareness at a physical, mental and emotional level on as well as off the mat.

Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Xin lưu ý: do quy mô lớp học nhỏ, chúng tôi yêu cầu các gia đình chỉ đăng ký cho các lớp học mà bạn có thể tham dự. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

event_name: New Technologies: Electronic Inventor Lab with AI Coding
event_description: What if    you could invent the machine to feed your dog when it's hungry, or the    clothing that lights up to the rhythms of your heart beat? In this hands-on    course we’ll use AI to do the coding while we focus on learning to use    programmable microcontrollers (Arduinos) to interface with the physical world    through sensors, animating LED displays, motors, and more. Moving from group    projects to individual inventions, you will learn the principles and theory    of practical electronics and circuit building, as well as best practices for    creating AI generated code that can enable your creative power. Learn how to    get your ideas and inventions out of your head and into existence. No    experience is required. Basic electronics supplies are provided for the    class, but there’s an additional material fee of $40. A paid subscription to    an AI service such as ChatGPT or Gemini is recommended. Repeat students are    welcomed and can work on their ongoing projects. This class pairs well with a    Digital Fab Lab course that focuses on building and fabrication.

Discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats—an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

Join us    for this class exploring one of the oldest photographic processes, the    cyanotype. Previous experience with    cyanotype is required.

Drawing  With Dynamic Value  In this class you will  develop a dynamic, value-based approach to drawing that can strengthen both  technical skill and creative expression. Learn the principles of shading and  how to apply them in drawings from life or imagination. We’ll explore how to  “paint” with powdered charcoal, use blending stumps for smooth transitions,  simplify complex scenes through reductive value, and work effectively on  toned paper. You’ll also investigate value using both charcoal and graphite,  gaining confidence in tools and techniques that bring form and depth to your  work. This class is open to all skill levels—whether you’re new to shading or  already comfortable with value but looking to expand your practice. A $138  model fee is included in the price of the class. Please bring requested  materials to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

Come to a  place where we build Deaf community, language and culture. The    Deaf Club will be meeting once a month on the first Friday of each month    during the season. The first    half of the evening is designed to support those learning American Sign    Language (ASL), including ASL students, and parents who have a child who is    Deaf or hard of hearing. This is a drop-in program,    but a Recreation and Parks Play Pass or sign-in is required.

This class builds on the basic aquatic skills and water safety skills and concepts learned in level 1. Participants begin to perform skills at a slightly more advanced level and begin gaining rudimentary propulsive skills on both the front and the back. This level continues to focus on building more comfort and enjoyment in the water using songs, games and play. event_name: Painting with Botanicals: Line and Wash Techniques
event_description: This    workshop invites students into an immersive, hands-on exploration of    botanical art using the vibrant line and wash technique. Across four    sessions, each built around working from fresh, live flowers, participants    will develop essential watercolor and pen skills — from color mixing and    composition principles to proportion, texture, and edge control. Guided by    artist Marco Flavio of Out There Watercolors, this workshop emphasizes    drawing from life, building confidence through observation, and creating    expressive floral pieces that feel alive on the page. Every class balances    demonstration, guided practice, and personal exploration, culminating in a    final composition that brings together all the techniques learned. Materials    provided.

This    class introduces hand building techniques including pinch, coil, and slab    construction, and basic wheel throwing techniques of wedging, centering,    throwing cups and bowls, and trimming. Instructor provides individual    guidance for all skill levels. Surface decoration and glazing techniques will    also be explored. Clay is available for purchase at the studio with a    100-pound clay limit per session. No outside clay or glazes allowed. Students    must purchase a basic pottery tool kit prior to the first day of class.    Suggested materials list can be found at sharonartstudio.org. Students may    enroll in only one ceramics class per session. Note: New students (new to    ceramics or Sharon Art Studio) must attend the first three classes. All skill    levels welcome.

This    course offers beginner students an opportunity to learn and explore a variety    of ceramic techniques focusing on the potter's wheel. Students can work with    and explore different clays, including stoneware and porcelain. Our selection    of glazes is unsurpassed. We fire cone 10 reduction. No clay from the outside    is allowed. Clay is available for purchase from the studio. Limit 100lbs clay    per session. Students may enroll in only one ceramics class per session.    Because this is a class for beginners, you must attend the first three    classes.

Welcome to our 25th Annual SFRPD All-City Jr. Warriors Youth Basketball League in San Francisco! Our Jr. Warriors League depends on the generosity of volunteers to provide an opportunity for our youth (Kindergarten - 8th Grade) to learn the game of basketball in a recreational, supportive, and safe environment. Each team will have league games (6 or more) and weekly practices. Jr. Warriors League games will be played on Thursdays, Fridays, or Saturdays at different Recreation Centers depending on grade level. If you are interested in becoming a coach/assistant coach, referee, or scorekeeper, you do not need to have a high level of experience in basketball. Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

Painting with sponges, miniature cars, rollers and fingers all add to    the hands-on experience and keep little hands and minds engaged. Participating toddlers must be accompanied by a participating adult. As with    every art class, dress for a mess! Appropriate for toddlers 2 to 4 years,    accompanied by a participating adult.

On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

The primary purpose of the lifeguard training program is to provide entry-level lifeguard skills and knowledge to prevent, recognize, and respond to emergencies and to provide care for sudden illnesses until advanced medical personnel arrives and takes over. This program includes a lifeguard training course with aquatics-specific first aid and cardio-pulmonary resuscitation (CPR) training. Note: Participants MUST pass the pre-test on the first day of class. The test consists of the following: 300-yard swim; tread water for 2 minute without the use of arms; swim 20 yards, then surface dive to retrieve a 10-lb brick, swim back to the starting point with both hands on the brick, and climb out of the water without assistance, skill must be performed in under 1 minute 40 seconds. Depending on the skills of the participants and their comprehension of the materials presented, the participants may be dismissed early or need to stay later each day.

event_name: Mixed Media: Abstract and Figure-Hybrid Art
event_description: This    class emphasizes the power of inner vision—creating images from within,    rather than simply copying nature. While we will begin by studying and    imitating existing forms, the focus will shift toward transforming those    observations into original, expressive creations. The main goal of this    course is for students to discover their own unique visual style. By    exploring Surrealist, Cubist, and imitating ancient artistic influences,    students will experience the joy of creative transformation within oneself.      Students will first learn the principles of abstract geometric composition,    then move toward combining figurative or organic elements with abstraction.    The aim is to develop an individual artistic “flavor”—a step toward personal    originality.      Hands-on support will be provided throughout. No prior experience is    necessary. A $138 Model fee included in the price of the class. Please bring    supplies to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

Welcome to our 25th Annual SFRPD All-City Jr. Warriors Youth Basketball League in San Francisco! Our Jr. Warriors League depends on the generosity of volunteers to provide an opportunity for our youth (Kindergarten - 8th Grade) to learn the game of basketball in a recreational, supportive, and safe environment. Each team will have league games (6 or more) and weekly practices. Jr. Warriors League games will be played on Thursdays, Fridays, or Saturdays at different Recreation Centers depending on grade level. If you are interested in becoming a coach/assistant coach, referee, or scorekeeper, you do not need to have a high level of experience in basketball. Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats—an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

Enjoy structured league play with a focus on teamwork, consistency, and friendly competition. Great for those who have some experience and want to keep the momentum going!

Discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats—an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

Join us    for a one-day workshop exploring one of the oldest photographic processes,    the cyanotype. This alternative process produces a characteristic blue hued    photographic print. In this workshop participants will use found objects like    flowers, plants, or other common items to create unique photograms using the    cyanotype process. We will cover the basics of the process from mixing and    applying emulsion to exposure and development. Participants are encouraged to    bring their own objects with them on the day. Advice will be provided on    suitable objects.

Swim Academy is a new pilot program for first-time swimmers who have never taken a Level 1 swim class. Welcome to our 25th Annual SFRPD All-City Jr. Warriors Youth Basketball League in San Francisco! Our Jr. Warriors League depends on the generosity of volunteers to provide an opportunity for our youth (Kindergarten - 8th Grade) to learn the game of basketball in a recreational, supportive, and safe environment. Each team will have league games (6 or more) and weekly practices. Jr. Warriors League games will be played on Thursdays, Fridays, or Saturdays at different Recreation Centers depending on grade level. If you are interested in becoming a coach/assistant coach, referee, or scorekeeper, you do not need to have a high level of experience in basketball. Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

Swim Academy is a new pilot program for first-time swimmers who have never taken a Level 1 swim class. Students will start in Level 1 and have the opportunity to progress through Level 3 as they develop their skills. To move to the next level, swimmers must successfully pass the required exit skills. Enrollment in the next level is only offered in the following session, and only to those who meet the exit criteria—no exceptions. If a child does not pass their current level, they will not continue in the Academy at this time.

Welcome to our 25th Annual SFRPD All-City Jr. Warriors Youth Basketball League in San Francisco! Our Jr. Warriors League depends on the generosity of volunteers to provide an opportunity for our youth (Kindergarten - 8th Grade) to learn the game of basketball in a recreational, supportive, and safe environment. Each team will have league games (6 or more) and weekly practices. Jr. Warriors League games will be played on Thursdays, Fridays, or Saturdays at different Recreation Centers depending on grade level. If you are interested in becoming a coach/assistant coach, referee, or scorekeeper, you do not need to have a high level of experience in basketball. Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

Ready,    set, shoot! This 6-week archery course is designed just for girls who want to    build their skills, grow their confidence, and have a blast doing it.    Following the USA Archery curriculum, you'll learn how to shoot safely and    accurately while mastering proper form, scoring basics, and range etiquette.    Each session includes fun games, friendly challenges, and empowering    instruction in a supportive, all-girls environment. Whether you're brand new    or aiming to improve, this class is your target for fun and growth. All    equipment is provided—just bring your focus and fierce energy!

Join us this winter for the 27th Annual SFRPD Jose Coronado Futsal League! We'll form teams based on grade, skill level, and desired competition level (Recreational, Intermediate, or Advanced). Interested in coaching? Let us know! We'll guide you through our background check process and provide training and support throughout the season. Games are held on Sundays only, within a 4-hour window at one gym per division. The exact location depends on age group and team count; for example, Kindergarten games will be at Moscone Rec Center.Please note: there are no weekday practices. If your child already has a spot on an independent team or club, you’ll receive registration instructions from them. Players may only be registered on one team.

event_name: After School Program - Potrero Hill Wait List
event_description: **You are adding to the wait list only**The After School program is currently full. You are adding to the wait list for the 2025-26 school year. If a spot opens up and we are able to offer you a spot, we will reach out. This afterschool program only pick up participants from Starr King.  Our after school program is an experience that provides a safe and nurturing environment for youth in grades K-5 to develop life long recreation and leisure skills. Participants will receive homework assistance, be exposed to an environment that will promote literacy, encourage communication and empowerment skills while providing recreation activities that include sports, group games, arts and culture, community exploration and seasonal special events. All staff and volunteers receive background checks and are trained in safety skills. Start times may vary based on the school release time. The fee for the school year is $1,080. Parents will have the option to pay the entire fee upon registration. Payment plans are available. $270 is due upon registration and on the first day of October, January and March of the school year.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Experience  the thrill of portrait drawing with compressed and vine charcoal! After  facing the challenge of portraying our subject's likeness, our sensitivities  will be attuned to creative expression. During each class we'll sketch-out  guide lines by close observation of our subject, then freely apply bold  strokes of charcoal to create a dynamic composition. We'll each have a  completed portrait by the end of every meeting. The cost of the class  includes a $115 model fee. Please bring a drawing pad to class. Paints,  brushes, and other materials for class will be provided by your instructor.  Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

event_description: Discover the serene beauty of San Francisco’s waterways with a self-guided kayaking experience at either Lake Merced or China Basin. Paddle at your own pace as you explore the lake’s tranquil waters, diverse wildlife, and natural habitats—an ideal way to connect with nature and enjoy a refreshing outdoor adventure right in the city. Enrollment includes the rental of a tandem (two-person) kayak and covers up to two participants. Personal flotation devices are provided for all participants. Children 12 and under must be accompanied by an adult in the kayak. All participants must sign a release waiver on the day of their session. Instructional safety videos must be viewed prior to paddling; a link to the videos and waiver will be emailed the week before your scheduled time. Registered participants under the age of 12 must be accompanied on the water by a registered parent or guardian. Expect to get wet—please bring a towel and a change of clothes.

Playful    Intuitive Art Exploration is a fun and exploratory drawing and painting class    that gives folks an opportunity to express themselves creatively through    creating art and connecting with their intuition. We will be taking    inspiration from unique real-world images (centered around nature and    microscopic photography) which incorporate interesting colors, textures, and    shapes. You will learn basic drawing techniques using the elements of art and    will be experimenting with abstract and representational concepts using your    intuition as a guide. You get to be the orchestrator here. There is no right    or wrong in this class and no prior drawing experience is necessary! Join us    and have some fun!

Ukuleles can be borrowed for the class during class    time, but it is recommended that students bring their own so they may    practice at home between classes.

event_name: First Steps Excelsior (Playgroup, English, Spanish, Cantonese, Vietnamese)
event_description: Build healthy bonding and enjoy fun activities together, while learning about your child’s cognitive and emotional development. Activities include arts, movement, songs, and stories. For ages 6 – 36 months + parents/caregivers. Free to enroll! Please note: due to our small class size, we ask families to register only for the classes you are able to attend. If you are no longer able to attend a class, please cancel your registration or contact us at firststeps@fccenters.org. Thank you! Registration will open at 9:00 am on the 28th of each month.   ·Portola: Mondays and Wednesdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Excelsior: Tuesdays and Thursdays, 9:00-10:30 am · Visitacion Valley: Thursdays, 9:30-11:00 am. (18-36 months + caregiver) For more information or to join, contact Elsa at 415.715.6746 or firststeps@fccenters.org • • • Primeros Pasos (First Steps) es un espacio para que las familias aprendan juntas. Las maestras lo guiarán a usted y a sus pequeños a través de actividades que incluyen canciones, bailes, y lecturas divertidas. Para edades de 6–36 meses + cuidador/a. Gratis para inscribirse. Tenga en cuenta: debido a nuestro pequeño tamaño de clase, le pedimos a las familias que se registren solo para las clases a las que puede asistir. Si ya no puede asistir a una clase, cancele su registro o contáctenos en firststeps@fccenters.org. ¡Gracias! Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Xin lưu ý: do quy mô lớp học nhỏ, chúng tôi yêu cầu các gia đình chỉ đăng ký cho các lớp học mà bạn có thể tham dự. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

event_name: Woodworking in Small Spaces: Portable Workbenches!
event_description: Are you    interested in woodworking but like most city residents have limited space?    Have you built saw horses at the Randall and want to explore how to put them    to use? In this hands-on class you'll build a portable workbench that can    mount on those saw horses or at your kitchen table. From the classic hand    tools needed to make furniture (chisels, hand planes, measuring and marking    tools, and various types of saws) to small, portable power tools, you'll go    home with a deeper sense of what's possible in small spaces. Instructor Mike    Bray has decades of experience and scores of tricks and techniques for    working safely and accurately. A $100 materials fee is included in the cost    and covers the unique demands of the bench, including a bench vise, two    layers of finished ply, and hardwood framing. Prerequisite: Woodshop Safety    Orientation. Students who have not met the prerequisite will be withdrawn and    charged a 20% refund processing fee.

event_description: This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

event_description: Build healthy bonding and enjoy fun activities together, while learning about your child’s cognitive and emotional development. Please note: due to our small class size, we ask families to register only for the classes you are able to attend. If you are no longer able to attend a class, please cancel your registration or contact us at firststeps@fccenters.org. Thank you! Registration will open at 9:00 am on the 28th of each month. · Visitacion Valley: Thursdays, 9:30-11:00 am. (18-36 months + caregiver) For more information or to join, contact Elsa at 415.715.6746 or firststeps@fccenters.org • • • Primeros Pasos (First Steps) es un espacio para que las familias aprendan juntas. Las maestras lo guiarán a usted y a sus pequeños a través de actividades que incluyen canciones, bailes, y lecturas divertidas. Para edades de 6–36 meses + cuidador/a. Gratis para inscribirse. Tenga en cuenta: debido a nuestro pequeño tamaño de clase, le pedimos a las familias que se registren solo para las clases a las que puede asistir. Si ya no puede asistir a una clase, cancele su registro o contáctenos en firststeps@fccenters.org. ¡Gracias! Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. Các giáo viên của chúng tôi sẽ hướng dẫn bạn và con bạn thông qua các hoạt động hấp dẫn liên quan đến bài hát, điệu nhảy ngộ nghĩnh. Từ 6-36 tháng tuổi + cha mẹ/người chăm sóc. Ghi danh miễn phí. Xin lưu ý: do quy mô lớp học nhỏ, chúng tôi yêu cầu các gia đình chỉ đăng ký cho các lớp học mà bạn có thể tham dự. Nếu bạn không thể tham gia lớp học được nữa, vui lòng hủy đăng ký hoặc liên hệ với chúng tôi tại firststeps@fccenters.org. Cảm ơn! Cổng đăng ký sẽ mở vào lúc 9:00 sáng ngày 28 hàng tháng.

event_name: Playful Abstract Ecosystems in Pencil and Watercolor
event_description: When  we take time to truly look at the world around us, we often see amazing,  beautiful things that we may not have noticed before. Ecosystems are made up  of living things, non-living things, landscapes, and weather that make up a  system-- creating a bubble of life. In this playful, relaxed series we will  be exploring ecosystems in ways that are both literal and  conceptual--focusing on interesting visual occurrences in nature and noticing  some of the fascinating visual moments that may occur in our typical everyday  lives. We will be using visual information and inspiration from real-world  images to create interesting abstract work with pencil and watercolor paint  while touching on elements and principles of art such as value, shape, line,  and balance. You get to be the orchestrator here. There is no right or wrong  in this class and no experience is necessary! Please bring requested  materials to class. See materials list at sharonartstudio.org.

In  this creative and dynamic class we will explore printmaking with soft pastel,  watercolor, and acrylic painting opens up so many possibilities for artistic  expression. Each medium brings its own unique qualities to the artwork, and  when combined, they can create stunning textures, layers, and visual effects.  Participants will have the opportunity to experiment with different  techniques and materials, allowing for a truly multidimensional approach to  their artwork. It's a fantastic opportunity for artists to push their  boundaries and explore new ways of working with mixed media. Please bring  supplies to class. Materials list available at sharonartstudio.org.

event_name: Adult Swim - Improving Skills and Swimming Strokes
event_description: This class seeks to improve participants' proficiency in basic aquatic skills (including rotary breathing, surface dives and treading) and the six basic swimming strokes (i.e., front crawl, back crawl, butterfly, breaststroke, elementary backstroke and sidestroke). (The butterfly stroke is optional.) Participants also learn skills and concepts needed to stay safe around water, in addition to those needed to help themselves or others in an aquatic emergency.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

Las inscripciones se abrirán el día 28 de cada mes a las 9 de la mañana. • • • First Steps是適合孩子和家長一起學習的遊戲小組。 我們的老師將與您們一起歌曲、舞蹈、閲讀等活動。 免費報名。適合6-36個月的孩子 + 家長/監護人。 請注意：由於我們的班級規模較小，我們要求家庭只註冊您可以參加的課程。 如果您不能再上課，請取消註冊或通過 firststeps@fccenters.org 聯繫我們。 謝謝你! 每月28日上午9:00開始報名。 • • • First Steps là một nhóm trẻ mẫu giáo được giám sát bởi người lớn để các gia đình học tập cùng nhau. This    class introduces hand building techniques including pinch, coil, and slab    construction, and basic wheel throwing techniques of wedging, centering,    throwing cups and bowls, and trimming. Instructor provides individual    guidance for all skill levels. Surface decoration and glazing techniques will    also be explored. Clay is available for purchase at the studio with a    100-pound clay limit per session. No outside clay or glazes allowed. Students    must purchase a basic pottery tool kit prior to the first day of class.    Suggested materials list can be found at sharonartstudio.org. Students may    enroll in only one ceramics class per session. Note: New students (new to    ceramics or Sharon Art Studio) must attend the first three classes. All skill    levels welcome.

Instruction    of beginner and intermediate leaded glass techniques. Advanced students    work      on more sophisticated projects. Class fee includes introductory glass    project, use of tools and some materials.      Students will be responsible for purchasing materials for personal projects    (which can be costly). Material list      provided at first class. Glass cutting requires normal hand dexterity. New    students (new to glass or the studio)      must attend the first class to receive instruction that will not be    repeated. Advanced students: No grinding the      first 2 hours of the first class. Note: Students may enroll in only one    glass class per session. No glass fusing allowed during this class.

event_name: Advanced Figure Drawing: Space to Play
event_description: Please  note: this is an advanced level figure drawing class. Drawing experience  required. Figure drawing is an active process; an engagement with material  that is both physical and intellectual. In this class, students will be  encouraged to work in terms of process rather than making a finished product,  in order to foster curiosity and therefore, insight. Insights will be learned  through visual problem solving, exploring the looking and seeing  relationship, and the expression of touching marker to paper. This class is a  choose your own adventure, as it is completely self-directed. As soon as  class starts, we will dive into meditation as a group through deep  concentrated drawing time. Emphasis will be on gesture poses, working our way  up through short poses of various time lengths, and ending each class with 20  minute poses. In addition, our entire final class day will be spent on a long  pose. (Troubleshooting, corrections, and critiques of student work made upon  request to the instructor during 5 minute breaks between poses.) Price of the  model is included in the cost of the class. The cost includes a $115 model  fee. Please bring paper and drawing materials to class. Materials list  available at sharonartstudio.org.

event_name: Jewelry Workshop: Intro to Jewelry Design & Hand Sawing
event_description: Transform  your graphic drawings into stunning metal jewelry and art pieces using  fundamental metalsmithing techniques. This accessible course focuses on hand  sawing and piercing sheet metal to create dynamic components with minimal  tools. Students will explore the interplay of positive and negative space  while mastering essential hand sawing skills that form the foundation of  metalsmithing. Students can choose one or more depending on their ambition  level such as earrings, pendants, decorative window hangings, or brooches.  This course emphasizes creativity and personal expression through  metal--perfect for beginners and those looking to strengthen their  fundamental hand sawing skills. All tools and materials provided.

Our after school program is an experience that provides a safe and nurturing environment for youth in grades K-5 to develop life long recreation and leisure skills. Participants will receive homework assistance, be exposed to an environment that will promote literacy, encourage communication and empowerment skills while providing recreation activities that include sports, group games, arts and culture, community exploration and seasonal special events. All staff and volunteers receive background checks and are trained in safety skills. Start times may vary based on the school release time. The fee for the school year is $1080. Parents will have the option to pay the entire fee upon registration. Payment plans are available. $270.00 is due upon registration and on the first day of October, January and March of the school year.

event_description: Music & Movement / Música y movimiento Join us for a fun and engaging group where caregivers learn how to play with their children in ways that support key developmental stages and milestones. Through hands-on activities, guided play, and expert tips, you’ll discover how everyday moments can become powerful opportunities for learning and connection. Perfect for parents and caregivers of young children looking to build skills, confidence, and joyful bonds. Únase a nosotros en un grupo divertido y atractivo en el que los cuidadores aprenden a jugar con sus hijos de formas que favorecen las etapas y los hitos clave del desarrollo. A través de actividades prácticas, juegos guiados y consejos de expertos, descubrirá cómo los momentos cotidianos pueden convertirse en poderosas oportunidades para el aprendizaje y la conexión. Perfecto para padres y cuidadores de niños pequeños que desean desarrollar habilidades, confianza y vínculos afectivos. In  this beginner class, each student can expect to design and fabricate a unique  sterling silver stone set ring. Students will learn foundational  silversmithing techniques- cut metal with the jewelers saw, sand, file,  stamp, form, solder and create a bezel cup in order to fabricate their final  product. This class is a great opportunity to learn a new skill or brush up  on existing metalsmithing skills. All levels of experience are welcome.  Materials and tools are provided with the cost of the class, but please feel  free to bring your own cabochons and supplies. If this will be your first  ring and you would like to purchase your own cabochons to use in the class,  please purchase oval or circular. The Jewelry Studio is located on the upper  floor, with stair access only. For accommodations requests or accessibility  questions, please contact rpdaccess@sfgov.org or 415-831-6841. Please note  that submitting your request at least two weeks before the beginning of the  class will help ensure availability.

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

This level continues to focus on building more comfort and enjoyment in the water using songs, games and play. While introducing more structured play in the areas of bobbing, breath control, floating, gliding and kicking on front and back, in addition to arm rotations and other elementary skills. Children ages 3 and under are required to wear swim diapers while in the pool. The ratio is 1 adult per child. Swim classes are limited to one class per person per session.

This class builds on the basic aquatic skills and water safety skills and concepts learned in level 1. Participants begin to perform skills at a slightly more advanced level and begin gaining rudimentary propulsive skills on both the front and the back. This level marks the beginning of independent aquatic locomotion skills. Prerequisite- Completion of Level 1. Children must be 48 to participate. Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

event_name: Jewelry Workshop: Introduction to Precious Metal Clay
event_description: Create a    jewelry piece from beginning to end with this hands-on workshop. Participants    will explore the versatility of precious metal clay (PMC) to craft unique and    personalized jewelry pieces (rings/pendants/earrings). From designing to    firing, this class covers the entire process, allowing attendees to create    custom jewelry. Tools and materials provided. Please Note: The Jewelry Studio    is located on the upper floor, with stair access only. For accommodations    requests or accessibility questions, please contact rpdaccess@sfgov.org or    415-831-6841.  To help ensure    availability, please submit accommodation requests at least two weeks before    the start of the class.

This    hands-on class covers the basics in film camera usage starting with properly    loading your film, exposure, depth of field basics and more.  Please make sure to bring your film camera    and a roll of film.  35 mm and medium    format will be covered.  Please call    the Photo Center if you at 415-554-9522 if you have any questions about this    class.

An    Introduction to skateboarding.  Learn    the basics of skateboarding from balance, pushing, turning and cruising on    low impact ramps and surfaces.  We    offer a safe place for beginning skateboarders to learn how to stand on a    skateboard properly while maintaining our balance.  We will cover the safety aspects and “flow”    of skating flat ground obstacles/ramps.     We’ll also assist in basic skateboard maintenance and identify each    part of the skateboard.  Our    instructors are certified in teaching youth and helping kids and adults    navigate their way through the fundamentals of skateboarding.
Try your hand at a game that's fun for all ages! BINGO! All are welcome.

Join us for drop-in ping pong at Crocker Amazon—no registration needed, just bring your game face and paddle! Open to all skill levels, it's a fun and friendly way to stay active and meet fellow players.
Live    Ball is a new format which emphasizes on court competitive drills in a fun,    fast, & exciting game format. This tennis course is not for the entry    level beginning player.

Parkour builds physical and mental strength using only your environment and body so that you can move more quickly, confidently, and creatively. This class utilizes indoor and outdoor environments to teach the fundamentals or gives you a space to sharpen them if you already have a little experience. All you need is athletic shoes and a bottle of water.

Welcome to our 25th Annual SFRPD All-City Jr. Warriors Youth Basketball League in San Francisco! Our Jr. Warriors League depends on the generosity of volunteers to provide an opportunity for our youth (Kindergarten - 8th Grade) to learn the game of basketball in a recreational, supportive, and safe environment. Each team will have league games (6 or more) and weekly practices. Jr. Warriors League games will be played on Thursdays, Fridays, or Saturdays at different Recreation Centers depending on grade level. If you are interested in becoming a coach/assistant coach, referee, or scorekeeper, you do not need to have a high level of experience in basketball. Our league offers an annual coaching clinic and experienced coaches who are more than happy to provide advice.

Looking to shoot hoops, break a sweat, and meet fellow players? Drop by for open gym basketball. Whether you're practicing solo or jumping into a pickup game, there's always action on the court. Busiest times: Saturday mornings (9 AM–12 PM) & Tuesday nights (6–8 PM).

Join    us for San Francisco's annual indoor archery tournament at the County Fair    Building! Inspired by the International Vegas Shoot tournament, this event    welcomes archers of all levels for a thrilling competition. We encourage    archers of all backgrounds and experience levels to participate and enjoy the    excitement of tournament-style shooting! Adult distance will be at 20 yards    on 40cm target faces. Youth distance will be at 10 yards on 60cm target    faces. Bow categories are: Olympic Recurve, Barebow Recurve, Traditional,    Compound Freestyle, Compound Bowhunter, and Compound Barebow. Trophies will    be awarded after the event. Participants must provide own equipment. This    event is ADA-accessible and welcoming to all participants. Deadline to    register is Monday, March 7. Come    learn the potter's wheel with us! This friendly & supportive studio is    the perfect place to develop your throwing skills. You'll learn to wedge,    center, and pull up the clay walls of your wheel-thrown clay pieces. Begin    throwing cups & bowls and progress at your own pace to more advanced    forms like vases and plates. You'll learn glazing techniques, and work will    be fired in the Randall kilns. NOTE: New students must attend the first three    class meetings.

Get busy creating as we learn about, explore and practice with the exciting variety of mediums and tools in the Randall Museum's Art Studio! We'll workshop projects, techniques, and creative approaches in every class and see where the process leads us!

Let    the art adventures begin early! This playful, hands-on class is designed    especially for our youngest artists. Together, children and their caregivers    will use toys and familiar art tools to make this introduction to art extra    fun. Painting with sponges, miniature cars, rollers and fingers all add to    the hands-on experience and keep little hands and minds engaged. Our young    artists will also have the chance to explore alternative activities that    encourage social interaction and fine motor skills throughout each class.    Participating toddlers must be accompanied by a participating adult. As with    every art class, dress for a mess! Appropriate for toddlers 2 to 4 years,    accompanied by a participating adult.

Join us at the ultimate gaming hangout where you can build and play games with friends! Learn how to mod your favorite popular games, like Super Smash Bros using 2D and 3D graphics, how to host epic gaming tournaments, and create awesome online content by streaming, editing, and posting your own videos. All this happens in a safe, fun, and super chill environment where you can level up your skills and creativity.  This community gaming space is open to ages 10 and up. Participants are encouraged to bring their own device, and some tablets will be available to use during the gaming hang out.
4-on-4,  Full-Court drop-in games for 18+!

Karate originated in the Okinawa Islands of Japan and has branched out into many different styles. Karate Kidz is a structured class that teaches formalized, sequenced movements which represent offensive and defensive postures known as Kata. Students will also learn kicking, punching, blocking and other open hand techniques. Students will have the opportunity to purchase a uniform and belts for an extra fee.

Got a favorite movie? Ever wonder how the great movies got their magic? This class teaches you how! This class is an exploration of cinema style and technique through replication, imitation, creation of cinema, movies, TV, and net series. The class watches and analyzes famous movies, focusing on specific techniques, which they then replicate in class. First we watch it, then we do it! This class will use short scenes, script analysis, making short-films, lighting, camera drills, and students will practice acting/blocking tactics for movie success.

There is now a minimal fee for Indoor Zumba. Walk-up outdoor classes are free. Visit sfrecpark.org/zumba for a full list of current class information. Purchase a discounted multi-visit pass at sfrecpark.org/register under Passes & Memberships.

Are you    retired and looking for something new to explore?  Do you have time on a Tuesday afternoon and    are curious about trying drawing and painting in a fun, laid back    environment? Are you wanting to connect with your intuition, play, or    destress using art as a vehicle?     Playful Intuitive Art Exploration is a fun and exploratory drawing and    painting class that gives folks an opportunity to express themselves    creatively through creating art and connecting with their intuition. We will    be taking inspiration from unique real-world images (centered around nature    and microscopic photography) which incorporate interesting colors, textures,    and shapes. You will learn basic drawing techniques using the elements of art    and will be experimenting with abstract and representational concepts using    your intuition as a guide. You get to be the orchestrator here. There is no    right or wrong in this class and no prior drawing experience is necessary!    Join us and have some fun!

This    Class is for students that have achieved Orange Belt (7th Gup in Korean) and    above. Conceptual Knowledge is required. One should have already learned the    basic skills needed for advancement. The General Requirements 1 through 3    shows examples. The Pyung Form signifies the changing aspect of Tang Soo Do,    called the Turtle. The Turtle has peace of mind, it's the slow    steady controlled pace to success. Mind, Body, and Spirit. |

This class builds on the skills learned in Levels 1 and 2. Participants learn to swim the front crawl and elementary backstroke at rudimentary proficiency levels and are introduced to the scissors and dolphin kicks. Participants learn the survival float and increase the time duration for treading water. Participants also learn the rules for headfirst entries and begin to learn to enter the water headfirst from a seated position at poolside (if the water is 9 feet deep or deeper). On successful completion of Level 3, participants have achieved basic water competency in a pool environment. Prerequisite: Successful completion of Level 2. Children must be 48 to participate.  Registration is limited to one swim class per participant.

We look forward to spending three magical days with your little holiday helpers!

This class introduces hand building techniques including pinch, coil, and slab construction, and basic wheel throwing techniques of wedging, centering, throwing cups and bowls, and trimming. Instructor provides individual guidance for all skill levels. Surface decoration and glazing techniques will also be explored. Clay is available for purchase at the studio with a 100-pound clay limit per session. No outside clay or glazes allowed. Students must purchase a basic pottery tool kit prior to the first day of class. Suggested materials list can be found at sharonartstudio.org. Students may enroll in only one ceramics class per session. Note: New students (new to ceramics or Sharon Art Studio) must attend the first three classes. All skill levels welcome.

event_name: Jewelry Workshop: Basics of Custom Prong Setting
event_description: Take    your jewelry-making to the next level by learning to make a prong setting!    Students will expand upon their metalsmithing skills by learning how to craft    custom prongs, solder, and polish a sterling silver setting. Our wonderful    jewelry studio is outfitted with all the tools and equipment to take your    jewelry making to the next level and beyond. Students must have taken the    beginner course previously or demonstrate equivalent skills. Class fee    includes the use of tools and materials for one sterling silver prong    setting. Students who wish to use materials beyond what is provided need to    have the approval of the instructor and be responsible for purchasing and    safe storage. Additional silver and gemstones can be purchased in class for a    fee, payable to the instructor. Jewelry making requires normal hand    dexterity. Students must attend class on time to receive instruction that    will not be repeated. Tools and materials available. The Jewelry Studio is    located on the upper floor, with stair access only. For accommodations    requests or accessibility questions, please contact rpdaccess@sfgov.org or    415-831-6841. Please note that submitting your request at least two weeks    before the beginning of the class will help ensure availability.
